[1
Date: Tue, 15 Aug 2000 12:35:37 -0400 (EDT)
From: Jose Campione-Piccardo <Jose_Campione@hc-sc.gc.ca>

Hypotheses derived from jungle virology analogies and experience
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Charlie Calisher's questions [see; West Nile virus surveillance - USA:
questions 2000.3089 have never been easy to answer! The following are still
not answers to some of his questions, but working hypotheses derived from
jungle virology analogies and experience.
As an old virologist who conducted viral surveillance in tropical rain
forests, I remember that each level of the canopy has its own ecology and
mosquito species and variants tend to feed at defined levels. I ignore
whether this is true for the mosquito species involved in the transmission
of West Nile virus (WNV) in North America. However, assuming that crows are
the most important American host for WNV, one would presume that the _Culex_
species primarily feeding on them would be doing so early in the morning and
late in the afternoon. During these times crows are likely to be either
returning to their feeding areas or flocking to roost, and in either case
they are more likely to be perched on trees than hopping on the ground.
Therefore, one wonders whether mosquitoes feeding on crows at these levels
would readily fly down to feed on chicken at ground level and whether the
efficiency of chicken flocks as sentinel birds for WNV might not be
increased if they were elevated from ground to crow roosting levels. If the
mosquito does not come down to the chicken, then make the chicken come up to
the mosquito!
Lethargic howler monkeys infected with YFV fall from the canopy and bring
down hemagogus mosquitoes creating the conditions for humans to become
infected. Using this jungle analogy, it is likely that sick birds falling to
the ground would bring with them their mosquitoes and that being close to a
sick bird that just fell to the ground (particularly from its roosting site
at dusk, when mosquitoes are likely to be most active) may particularly
increase the risk of human beings becoming infected.
--
Jose Campione-Piccardo, M.D., Ph.D., R.S.M. (C.C.M.)
Laboratory Sciences Medical Officer
Centre for Infectious Disease Prevention and Control
Tunney's Pasture, LCDC Bldg. Postal Locator 0601E2
Ottawa, Ontario, Canada K1A 0L2
<jose_campione@hc-sc.gc.ca>
