Date: Mon, 14 Aug 2000 17:41:01 GMT-3
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

Some denominators
-----------------
The point was made by Charlie Calisher that we were seeing a great many
more numerators than denominators. Some denominators are now available at
the Connecticut State West Nile virus (WNV) website:
<http://dep.state.ct.us/mosquito/tstrslt.asp> which and can be accessed
from the ProMED-mail WNV Links page. They are derived as follows: "All
mosquitoes for the week of 8 Aug 2000 are negative for WNV and Eastern
equine encephalitis (EEE) virus, with the identification of a positive
isolation of WNV from Stamford already reported on 21 Jul 2000. Overall,
7227 mosquitoes (collected from 18 Jul through 27 Jul 2000) were tested
from 71 permanent state-wide sites as well as 3 supplemental sites in
Greenwich (1) and Stamford (2). In addition, the State will be placing 6
mosquito traps in 3 locations in Cheshire to test and assess mosquito
populations and test for WNV and EEE virus".
These figures indicate a minimum field infection rate (MIF) of 1:7000 for
the Stamford area. There may be something in the literature to indicate
whether that level has been significant in past St. Louis encephalitis
virus outbreaks.
Over the past week, an increase has been noticed in daily mosquito
collections rising from an average of 1000 a day to 4000 a day. Most are
floodwater mosquitoes from the recent rain.
Statewide, 70 000 mosquitoes have been tested, all negative for WNV or EEE
with the identification of a positive isolation of WNV from Stamford
already reported.
