[4
Date: Mon, 14 Aug 2000 13:51:48 GMT-3
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Some responses to points raised by Eleanor Kellon in West Nile virus
surveillance - USA: Questions (04)
--------------------------------------------------------------------
(1) "I would like to know why sporadic spraying efforts should give anyone a
sense of security......?".
After each spray, a large number of adult mosquitoes, including infected
adults, are killed. Adults emerging post-spray have to find a blood meal. If
they find an infected bird, it still takes a few days for the virus to pass
from the gut to the salivary glands, plus the mosquito may not need another
blood meal until after it has matured and laid its eggs, so there cannot be
any transmission for a few days. Hence daily spraying is not necessary.
(2) "......it is not always/usually clear what test results are being used
to "confirm" West Nile virus (WNV) infection".
That may be so in the context of human infection, but Dr Laura Kramer of
the New York State Wadsworth Center's Arbovirus Laboratory has made it
absolutely clear what tests are being used in the State lab for confirming
WNV infection in birds and mosquitoes -- see: West Nile virus, crow - USA
(New York) (05) subsection.
(3) I can only assume that if a single CSF IgM is being used, [diagnosis
must be based on presumption..........
CDC has shown that WNV IgM lasts more than 200 days in some cases, so it may
persist since last year's outbreak. The post-epidemic survey in Queens showed
that hundreds of people had been infected without being ill. What is missing
from the information handed out is the titer of the IgM antibody. In old
cases this should be lower then in current cases.
(4) A pressing need is to find an effective vaccine.
There is no licensed vaccine available for Eastern or Western equine or St.
Louis encephalitis, which together kill each year perhaps as many people as
were killed by WNV last year. Unless there is a huge demand, there will be
no commercial incentive to produce the vaccine.
