Date: Fri, 18 Aug 2000 09:10:44 -0400
From: Eleanor Kellon <kell@epix.net>

A further question from Eleanor Kellon
--------------------------------------
In "West Nile virus Surveillance - USA (26)" New York City Health
Commissioner Neal L. Cohen, M.D. was quoted as saying on Aug 17 that " This
morning 23 mosquito pools from Staten Island, 3 mosquito pools from Central
Park, Manhattan, one mosquito pool from Hunts Point in the Bronx, one crow
from Northern Manhattan, one crow from Central Park and one crow from
Whitestone, Queens have tested positive for West Nile virus. These findings
were reported to the City Health Department yesterday by the New York State
Department of Health. As a result of this information, the City will apply
pesticides to reduce the number of potentially infected mosquitoes at
several locations city-wide over the next several days.
Whereas an Associated Press report dated Wednesday 16 Aug indicated that
"Health officials are escalating the battle against the West Nile virus with
a one-two punch of ground spraying and the season's first aerial spraying.
After another round of ground spraying on Wednesday evening, the first
aerial assault, with the pesticide Anvil, is scheduled for Thursday night on
Staten Island and in the Canarsie section of Brooklyn".
I am assuming from the fact (1) that they didn't specifically mention that
the positives were samples collected before spraying, and (2) that the
decision has been made to add aerial spray, that the most recent positives,
including the large number of positive mosquito pools on Staten island, were
collected after ground spraying had commenced.
Can anyone confirm this?
--
Eleanor Kellon, VMD
Technical Editor
Horse Journal
<kell@epix.net>
